<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-096-444  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 096 444.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  Jan 18 1989 n1444 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>More power to your laser! (David Sarnoff Research Centrebreakthrough - includes related article on 'the Grating SurfaceEmitter')</TITLE><AUTHOR>Baker, Stan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The David Sarnoff Research Center at Princeton, NJ has developednew laser technologies that are expected to break through thespeed limiting restrictions of wired interconnects in computers.andO;The Center developed a semiconductor laser diode structure thatemits more than a hundred times the light power of current laserchips in nearly nondiverging beams.andP;  Developers claim that the newpower levels and beam coherency elevate solid-state lasers beyondthe capabilities of gas lasers.andP;  The most important development isthat the integration with silicon will make possiblesemiconductors that can talk to each other using laser beamsinstead of wires.andP;  The new laser is called a Grating SurfaceEmitting Array.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Laser and Infrared CommunicationCommunications TechnologySemiconductorsResearch and Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Surface emitting array. (chart)Integrated optoelectronic circuit: GaAs and InGaAsP on siliconfabrication. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>